<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Definitions (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

> [!NOTE]
> **Unit Testing** is a level of software testing where individual units/components of a software are tested in isolation from the rest of the system. The smallest testable part of an application — typically a method, function, or class — is verified against expected behaviour.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **JUnit** is an open-source, Java-based **unit testing framework** that follows the **xUnit architecture**. It provides annotations, assertions, and a test runner to automate the execution and reporting of repeatable test cases. JUnit 5 (current stable version) is built on the **Jupiter API** and uses `@Test`, `@BeforeEach`, `@AfterEach`, etc.

> [!NOTE]
> **Mutation Testing** is a fault-based testing technique that evaluates the **quality of an existing test suite** by deliberately injecting small syntactic faults (*mutations*) into the program source code and checking whether the test cases can detect (*kill*) them.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> A **mutant** is a slightly altered version of the original program obtained by applying a single *mutation operator* (e.g., replacing `>` with `>=`, replacing `+` with `-`). A mutant is said to be **killed** if at least one test case fails when run against the mutated code.

---

## 1.2 Conceptual Analogy — Plain English Intuition

| Concept | Real-World Analogy | Easy Intuition |
|---|---|---|
| **Unit Testing** | A car mechanic testing each spark plug individually before assembling the engine | Check the smallest *part* before checking the *whole* |
| **JUnit Framework** | A standardised test bench that automatically starts the car, records RPM, fuel use, and prints a report card | Automates the boring repetitive checking |
| **Mutation Testing** | Trainer hides 20 spelling mistakes in a student's essay. If the proof-reader spots 18 → **Mutation Score = 90%** | A *meta-test* that checks whether your tests are sharp enough |
| **Killed Mutant** | The proof-reader caught the mistake | Test caught the injected fault |
| **Live Mutant** | The proof-reader missed the mistake | Test failed to detect the fault |
| **Equivalent Mutant** | Trainer wrote "colour" while original had "color" — same meaning, cannot be killed | A mutant that is functionally identical to the original — unkillable by design |

> [!TIP]
> **Why this matters in KTU exams:** Questions often appear as *"Explain how JUnit automates unit testing with a case study"* or *"Differentiate mutation testing from unit testing."* Memorise the lifecycle annotations and mutation-score formula — they are **guaranteed high-yield items**.

---

## 1.3 Key Standard Metrics in Bold

- **Mutation Score (MS)** — Percentage of non-equivalent mutants killed by a test suite.
- **Test Coverage** — Percentage of code lines/branches exercised by tests.
- **Mutation Operator** — A transformation rule applied to source code to create mutants.
- **Equivalent Mutant** — A mutant that is functionally identical to the original program.
- **Assertion** — A statement that verifies an expected condition; fails the test if false.
- **Test Fixture** — The fixed state used as a baseline for running tests.
- **CI/CD Pipeline** — Continuous Integration / Continuous Deployment workflow where JUnit tests run automatically on each code commit.

---

## 1.4 Why a Case Study?

> [!IMPORTANT]
> A **case study** in the KTU context means applying JUnit to a *concrete program* (e.g., a `Calculator`, `BankAccount`, or `LoginValidator` class), then using a **mutation testing tool** (typically **PIT / Pitest** for Java) to assess how strong the test cases are. This demonstrates that simply having *passing tests* is **not enough** — the tests must be *sensitive enough* to catch realistic faults.

<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Anatomy of a JUnit 5 Test Class — Structured Walk-Through

JUnit 5 (Jupiter) follows a strict **lifecycle** for every test method. Understanding this is essential for both theory questions and lab practicals.

### 2.1.1 Core JUnit 5 Annotations

| Annotation | When it Runs | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `@Test` | Marks a method as a test case | The actual verification logic |
| `@BeforeEach` | Before *every* `@Test` method | Initialise fresh test data |
| `@AfterEach` | After *every* `@Test` method | Clean up resources |
| `@BeforeAll` | Once, before all tests in the class | One-time expensive setup (must be `static`) |
| `@AfterAll` | Once, after all tests in the class | One-time teardown (must be `static`) |
| `@DisplayName` | — | Gives a human-readable test name |
| `@Disabled` | Skips the test | Temporarily exclude a test |
| `@Nested` | Groups related tests | Hierarchical test organisation |
| `@ParameterizedTest` | Runs test multiple times | Data-driven testing with `@ValueSource`, `@CsvSource` |
| `@Order(n)` | Defines execution order | Useful when tests depend on sequence |
| `assertTimeout` | Fails test if method exceeds time | Performance assertion |
| `assertThrows` | Verifies expected exception is raised | Negative-path testing |

### 2.1.2 Common Assertion Methods (from `org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions`)

- `assertEquals(expected, actual)` — strict equality check.
- `assertNotEquals(unexpected, actual)` — inequality check.
- `assertTrue(condition)` / `assertFalse(condition)` — boolean check.
- `assertNull(object)` / `assertNotNull(object)` — nullability check.
- `assertSame(expected, actual)` / `assertNotSame(...)` — reference identity.
- `assertArrayEquals(expected, actual)` — array content equality.
- `assertThrows(Class, Executable)` — verifies an exception is thrown.
- `assertAll(...)` — group of assertions, all run even if one fails.
- `fail(message)` — unconditionally fail.

### 2.1.3 The JUnit Test Lifecycle (Execution Order)

1. JVM loads the test class.
2. `static` initialiser block executes.
3. `@BeforeAll` method executes **once**.
4. For each `@Test` method:
   - a. A *new instance* of the test class is created.
   - b. `@BeforeEach` method executes.
   - c. The `@Test` method executes.
   - d. `@AfterEach` method executes.
5. `@AfterAll` method executes **once**.
6. Test report is generated (pass/fail counts, timings).

> [!TIP]
> **A common exam trick:** *"Why does JUnit create a new instance of the test class for every @Test method?"* — Answer: To guarantee **test isolation**; one test's state must never leak into another.

---

## 2.2 Mutation Testing — Theory of Operation

### 2.2.1 Step-by-Step Logic

1. **Start** with the original (correct) program `P`.
2. Apply a **mutation operator** (a syntactic transformation rule) to one location in `P`, producing a mutated program `M` (a *mutant*).
3. Compile `M` and run the existing test suite `T` against it.
4. **Classify the mutant** as one of:
   - **Killed** — at least one test in `T` fails on `M`.
   - **Live (survived)** — all tests in `T` pass on `M` (i.e., tests were too weak).
   - **Equivalent** — `M` is semantically identical to `P`; cannot be killed.
5. Repeat for many mutants to compute the **Mutation Score**.
6. If mutation score is low, **strengthen the test suite** by adding new assertions or test cases, then re-run.

### 2.2.2 Categories of Mutation Operators

| Category | Example Operators | Effect on Code |
|---|---|---|
| **Arithmetic** | AOR — Arithmetic Operator Replacement | `+` → `-`, `*` → `/`, `+` → `*` |
| **Relational** | ROR — Relational Operator Replacement | `>` → `>=`, `==` → `!=`, `<` → `<=` |
| **Logical** | LOR — Logical Operator Replacement | `&&` → `\|\|`, `!a` → `a` |
| **Conditional** | COD — Conditional Operator Deletion | Removes `if` conditions |
| **Negation** | Insert logical NOT | `a == b` → `a != b` |
| **Constant** | Replace constants with 0, 1, -1 | `x = 5` → `x = 0` |
| **Return Value** | Return 0 / null for non-void methods | `return x` → `return 0` |
| **Statement Deletion** | SDL — delete a statement | `x++;` removed |
| **Method Call Deletion** | Remove a method invocation | `list.add(x)` deleted |

> [!NOTE]
> In KTU exams, the **most-asked** mutation operators are **AOR, ROR, and LOR**. Commit these three acronyms to memory.

### 2.2.3 The Mutation Testing Workflow (End-to-End)

```
[Source Program P]
       │
       ▼
[Mutation Engine] ─── applies mutation operators ──► [Mutant M1, M2, ..., Mn]
       │
       ▼
[Compile Mutants]
       │
       ▼
[Run Test Suite T against each Mutant]
       │
       ├── Killed?     → record kill
       ├── Live?       → record survival
       └── Equivalent? → flag, exclude from score
       │
       ▼
[Compute Mutation Score]
       │
       ▼
[Generate Mutation Report (HTML / XML)]
```

### 2.2.4 Why Mutation Testing is Powerful

- **Code coverage is not enough.** A test can achieve 100% line coverage yet miss real bugs. Mutation testing injects *realistic* faults and checks if tests notice.
- **Identifies weak assertions.** A test that calls `add(2, 3)` and only checks `assertNotNull(result)` will *survive* many mutants.
- **Measures test-suite *adequacy***, not just *existence*.

---

## 2.3 KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The following table is **must-memorise** for ESE. Examiner's favourite derivations come straight from here.

| # | Concept | Formula / Definition | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | **Mutation Score (MS)** | $MS \;=\; \dfrac{M_k}{M_t \;-\; M_{eq}} \;\times\; 100$ | $M_k$ = killed, $M_t$ = total mutants, $M_{eq}$ = equivalent mutants |
| 2 | **Simplified MS** (excluding equivalent mutants separately) | $MS \;\approx\; \dfrac{M_k}{M_t} \times 100$ | Used when equivalent mutants unknown |
| 3 | **Mutant Kill Rate** | $\text{Kill Rate} = \dfrac{M_k}{M_t - M_{eq}}$ | Fractional form, often shown as decimal |
| 4 | **Live (Survived) Mutants** | $M_{live} = M_t - M_k - M_{eq}$ | Surviving but not equivalent |
| 5 | **Line Coverage** | $LC = \dfrac{L_{executed}}{L_{total}} \times 100$ | Weakest coverage metric |
| 6 | **Branch Coverage** | $BC = \dfrac{B_{executed}}{B_{total}} \times 100$ | Stronger than line coverage |
| 7 | **Cyclomatic Complexity** | $V(G) = E - N + 2P$ | $E$ = edges, $N$ = nodes, $P$ = connected components |
| 8 | **Mutation Adequacy Criterion** | $MS \ge 80\%$ | Industry rule-of-thumb for "good" test suite |
| 9 | **Equivalent Mutant Percentage** | $E\% = \dfrac{M_{eq}}{M_t} \times 100$ | Should be minimised by smart operators |
| 10 | **Cost Ratio** | $\text{Cost} = \dfrac{\text{Mutation runs}}{\text{Test runs}}$ | Mutation testing is ~$n \times$ more expensive |

> [!WARNING]
> **LaTeX Isolation Rule:** In the rendered markdown above, every `$$` block has a blank line before and after it. The vertical bars inside formulas like $\vert$ are written as $\mid$ to avoid breaking the markdown table. Do **not** type `|x|` directly inside a table cell.

---

## 2.4 Real-World Engineering Utility

| Domain | How This Topic is Applied |
|---|---|
| **Banking Software** | JUnit tests run on every commit via Jenkins; PIT runs nightly to catch weak assertions. |
| **Android App Dev** | JUnit + Espresso + Robolectric for unit + UI tests; mutation testing in continuous QA. |
| **Microservices** | JUnit + Mockito for unit tests of each service; PIT enforces contract correctness. |
| **Open-Source Projects** | SonarQube + PIT integrated into GitHub Actions; badges show coverage and mutation score. |
| **Aerospace / Automotive** | DO-178C / ISO 26262 require test-adequacy evidence — mutation score reports are accepted as proof. |

<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Case Study: The `BankAccount` Class

We will work with a small, exam-friendly Java class throughout this section. KTU loves this kind of class because it is short, has `if` branches, returns numbers, and throws exceptions — i.e., it is a **mutation-magnet**.

### 3.1.1 The Program Under Test (PUT)

```java
// File: BankAccount.java
public class BankAccount {

    private double balance;
    private String owner;

    public BankAccount(String owner, double initialBalance) {
        this.owner = owner;
        this.balance = initialBalance;
    }

    // Deposit a positive amount; returns new balance
    public double deposit(double amount) {
        if (amount <= 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Amount must be positive");
        }
        balance = balance + amount;
        return balance;
    }

    // Withdraw if sufficient funds exist; returns new balance
    public double withdraw(double amount) {
        if (amount <= 0) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Amount must be positive");
        }
        if (amount > balance) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Insufficient funds");
        }
        balance = balance - amount;
        return balance;
    }

    public double getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }

    public boolean isOverdrawn() {
        return balance < 0;
    }
}
```

---

## 3.2 Step-by-Step: Writing a JUnit 5 Test Class

```java
// File: BankAccountTest.java
import org.junit.jupiter.api.*;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.*;

class BankAccountTest {

    private BankAccount account;

    @BeforeEach
    void setUp() {
        // Fresh account before every test
        account = new BankAccount("Alice", 1000.00);
    }

    @Test
    @DisplayName("Deposit of positive amount increases balance correctly")
    void testDepositPositive() {
        double newBalance = account.deposit(500);
        assertEquals(1500.00, newBalance, 0.001);
        assertEquals(1500.00, account.getBalance(), 0.001);
    }

    @Test
    @DisplayName("Deposit of zero throws IllegalArgumentException")
    void testDepositZeroThrows() {
        assertThrows(IllegalArgumentException.class,
                     () -> account.deposit(0));
    }

    @Test
    @DisplayName("Deposit of negative amount throws IllegalArgumentException")
    void testDepositNegativeThrows() {
        assertThrows(IllegalArgumentException.class,
                     () -> account.deposit(-100));
    }

    @Test
    @DisplayName("Withdraw within balance reduces balance correctly")
    void testWithdrawValid() {
        double newBalance = account.withdraw(300);
        assertEquals(700.00, newBalance, 0.001);
    }

    @Test
    @DisplayName("Withdraw exceeding balance throws IllegalArgumentException")
    void testWithdrawInsufficient() {
        assertThrows(IllegalArgumentException.class,
                     () -> account.withdraw(5000));
    }

    @Test
    @DisplayName("isOverdrawn returns false when balance is positive")
    void testNotOverdrawn() {
        assertFalse(account.isOverdrawn());
    }

    @AfterEach
    void tearDown() {
        account = null;
    }
}
```

### Explanation of every key JUnit element

1. `@BeforeEach setUp()` — guarantees every test begins with a fresh `BankAccount("Alice", 1000)`. This is the **test fixture**.
2. `@DisplayName(...)` — replaces cryptic method names with readable descriptions in the test report.
3. `assertEquals(expected, actual, delta)` — the `delta = 0.001` is needed because `double` comparisons can suffer from floating-point rounding.
4. `assertThrows(Class, Executable)` — uses a **lambda** to invoke the method that should throw. If no exception (or the wrong one) is thrown, the test fails.
5. `@AfterEach tearDown()` — releases references; helps garbage collection.

---

## 3.3 Step-by-Step Mutation Analysis of `BankAccount`

Let us apply the **ROR** (Relational Operator Replacement) mutation operator to `deposit()`.

### 3.3.1 Original Code

```java
public double deposit(double amount) {
    if (amount <= 0) {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Amount must be positive");
    }
    balance = balance + amount;
    return balance;
}
```

### 3.3.2 Mutation 1: ROR — `<=` becomes `<`

```java
public double deposit(double amount) {
    if (amount < 0) {                              // mutated < =
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Amount must be positive");
    }
    balance = balance + amount;
    return balance;
}
```

- **Test case:** `testDepositZeroThrows` calls `deposit(0)`.
- **Original behaviour:** `0 <= 0` is `true` → exception is thrown → test **passes**.
- **Mutant behaviour:** `0 < 0` is `false` → no exception is thrown → test **fails**.
- **Result:** Mutant is **KILLED** ✓

### 3.3.3 Mutation 2: AOR — `+` becomes `-`

```java
public double deposit(double amount) {
    if (amount <= 0) {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Amount must be positive");
    }
    balance = balance - amount;                    // mutated + -
    return balance;
}
```

- **Test case:** `testDepositPositive` calls `deposit(500)`.
- **Original:** balance goes from `1000` to `1500`.
- **Mutant:** balance goes from `1000` to `500`.
- **Assertion** `assertEquals(1500, newBalance, 0.001)` **fails** on mutant.
- **Result:** Mutant is **KILLED** ✓

### 3.3.4 Mutation 3: Live (Survived) Mutant — AOR `+` to `*`

```java
public double deposit(double amount) {
    if (amount <= 0) {
        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Amount must be positive");
    }
    balance = balance * amount;                    // mutated + *
    return balance;
}
```

- Test `testDepositPositive` calls `deposit(500)`. Original returns `1500`. Mutant returns `1000 * 500 = 500000`.
- Assertion **fails** → Mutant **killed** ✓

### 3.3.5 Mutation 4: Equivalent Mutant Example (Hypothetical)

```java
public boolean isOverdrawn() {
    return balance < 0;     // Replace < with <= but balance is never < 0
}
```

- In this class, `balance` is never set to a negative value (the `withdraw` method prevents it). So `balance < 0` and `balance <= -0.0001` (or any logically equivalent variant) produce the **same output for every reachable test case**.
- Such a mutant is **equivalent** and is **excluded** from the mutation score.

---

## 3.4 Step-by-Step: Computing the Mutation Score (Full Worked Example)

Suppose our mutation engine generates the following 10 mutants for `BankAccount`:

| Mutant # | Operator | Location | Killed? | Equivalent? |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| M1 | ROR (`<=` → `<`) | `deposit` | Yes | No |
| M2 | ROR (`<=` → `>`) | `deposit` | Yes | No |
| M3 | AOR (`+` → `-`) | `deposit` | Yes | No |
| M4 | AOR (`+` → `*`) | `deposit` | Yes | No |
| M5 | ROR (`>` → `>=`) | `withdraw` | Yes | No |
| M6 | AOR (`-` → `+`) | `withdraw` | Yes | No |
| M7 | LOR (`&&` → `\|\|`) | (no such operator) | — | — |
| M8 | COD (remove `if`) | `withdraw` insufficient check | No (survived) | No |
| M9 | Return `0` instead of balance | `getBalance` | No (survived) | No |
| M10 | ROR (`<` → `<=`) | `isOverdrawn` | — | Yes (equivalent) |

### Analytical computation

- Total mutants generated: $M_t = 10$ (we count M1–M10, M7 never existed so it drops out — let us adjust: practical $M_t = 9$ excluding the non-applicable slot)
- Equivalent mutants: $M_{eq} = 1$ (M10)
- Killed mutants: $M_k = 6$ (M1, M2, M3, M4, M5, M6)
- Live mutants: $M_{live} = 9 - 6 - 1 = 2$ (M8, M9)

### Derivation of the Mutation Score

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Step 1: Identify the variables} \quad & M_k = 6,\;\; M_t = 9,\;\; M_{eq} = 1 \\[6pt]
\text{Step 2: Subtract equivalent mutants from denominator} \quad & M_t - M_{eq} = 9 - 1 = 8 \\[6pt]
\text{Step 3: Apply the MS formula} \quad & MS = \frac{M_k}{M_t - M_{eq}} \times 100 \\[6pt]
\text{Step 4: Substitute} \quad & MS = \frac{6}{8} \times 100 \\[6pt]
\text{Step 5: Simplify} \quad & MS = 0.75 \times 100 = 75\% \\[6pt]
\text{Step 6: Interpret} \quad & \text{The test suite kills 75\% of non-equivalent mutants.} \\
& \text{Below 80\% threshold → strengthen tests for M8, M9.}
\end{aligned}
$$

> [!NOTE]
> **Interpretation:** With $MS = 75\%$, the suite is **adequate but not excellent**. The two survived mutants (M8, M9) reveal that the suite lacks a test that exercises the case of *withdrawing more than balance with the conditional removed* and a test that *verifies balance value explicitly after multiple transactions*. We would add two more test cases to kill M8 and M9, raising the score to $8/8 = 100\%$.

---

## 3.5 Step-by-Step: Strengthening the Test Suite

```java
// NEW TEST — kills mutant M8 (COD — removed insufficient-funds check)
@Test
@DisplayName("Withdraw exceeding balance must throw, even with edge amounts")
void testWithdrawExceedsBalanceBoundary() {
    assertThrows(IllegalArgumentException.class,
                 () -> account.withdraw(1000.01));
    assertThrows(IllegalArgumentException.class,
                 () -> account.withdraw(999999.99));
}

// NEW TEST — kills mutant M9 (return 0 instead of balance)
@Test
@DisplayName("Balance after several transactions equals expected cumulative value")
void testBalanceAfterMultipleOperations() {
    account.deposit(100);    // 1100
    account.withdraw(50);    // 1050
    account.deposit(200);    // 1250
    assertEquals(1250.00, account.getBalance(), 0.001);
}
```

After adding these, we re-run the mutation engine and the new score is $100\%$. The case study is now complete.

---

## 3.6 Comparison Matrix: JUnit Test Life-cycle vs. Mutation Testing Life-cycle

| Phase | JUnit (Unit Testing) | Mutation Testing |
|---|---|---|
| **Input** | Source code + Test cases | Source code + Existing test suite |
| **Action** | Execute tests on original code | Execute same test suite on *mutated* code |
| **Pass condition** | All tests pass | All mutants killed |
| **Metric** | Pass / Fail count, Coverage % | Mutation Score (%) |
| **Output** | Test report (HTML / XML) | Mutation report (HTML / XML) — green/red per mutant |
| **Tool (Java)** | JUnit 5, TestNG | PIT (Pitest), MuJava, Major |
| **Cost** | Low (one execution per test) | High (one execution per mutant) |
| **Purpose** | Verify functional correctness | Verify test suite *strength* |

