# 4. Structural Diagrams & Schematics

## 4.1 JUnit 5 Test Execution Lifecycle (Mermaid Flowchart)

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[JVM Loads Test Class] --> B[Run static initialiser]
    B --> C["@BeforeAll method runs ONCE"]
    C --> D{For each @Test method}
    D --> E[Create new test-class instance]
    E --> F["@BeforeEach method runs"]
    F --> G[Execute @Test method body]
    G --> H{All assertions pass?}
    H -- Yes --> I[Mark test as PASSED]
    H -- No --> J[Mark test as FAILED with stack trace]
    I --> K["@AfterEach method runs"]
    J --> K
    K --> L{More @Test methods?}
    L -- Yes --> D
    L -- No --> M["@AfterAll method runs ONCE"]
    M --> N[Generate Test Report HTML/XML]
    N --> O[End]
```

**Reading the diagram:** Every box is a *node*, every arrow is a *flow*. Notice the `D` decision diamond that loops back to itself — this represents the iteration over all `@Test` methods. Each iteration creates a **fresh** instance to guarantee test isolation.

---

## 4.2 Mutation Testing Workflow (Mermaid Block Diagram)

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    subgraph InputStage["INPUT"]
        P[Original Program P]
        T[Existing Test Suite T]
    end

    subgraph EngineStage["MUTATION ENGINE"]
        OP[Mutation Operators Library e.g. AOR, ROR, LOR]
    end

    subgraph MutantGen["MUTANT GENERATION"]
        M1[Mutant M1]
        M2[Mutant M2]
        M3[Mutant M3]
        Mn[Mutant Mn]
    end

    subgraph ExecStage["EXECUTION SUBSYSTEM"]
        COMP[Compile Mutant]
        RUN[Run Test Suite T on Mutant]
    end

    subgraph ClassifyStage["CLASSIFICATION"]
        KILLED[Killed Mutant]
        LIVE[Live Survived Mutant]
        EQUIV[Equivalent Mutant]
    end

    subgraph ReportStage["REPORTING"]
        CALC[Compute Mutation Score MS]
        HTML[HTML / XML Mutation Report]
    end

    P --> OP
    OP --> M1
    OP --> M2
    OP --> M3
    OP --> Mn
    T --> RUN
    M1 --> COMP
    M2 --> COMP
    M3 --> COMP
    Mn --> COMP
    COMP --> RUN
    RUN --> KILLED
    RUN --> LIVE
    RUN --> EQUIV
    KILLED --> CALC
    LIVE --> CALC
    EQUIV --> CALC
    CALC --> HTML
```

**Reading the diagram:** Five labelled subgraphs represent the **five stages** of mutation testing. The arrows leaving `OP` (Mutation Operators Library) fan out to multiple mutants (M1, M2, M3 … Mn) — this is the **fan-out** of the mutation generation step. Equivalent mutants feed into the score calculation but are subtracted in the denominator — see formula in §2.3.

---

## 4.3 JUnit Assertion Decision Tree

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Need to verify a condition?] --> B{Is expected value known?}
    B -- Yes --> C[Use assertEquals expected, actual]
    B -- No --> D{Boolean condition?}
    D -- Yes --> E["assertTrue / assertFalse"]
    D -- No --> F{Null check needed?}
    F -- Yes --> G[assertNull / assertNotNull]
    F -- No --> H{Exception expected?}
    H -- Yes --> I[assertThrows Class, Executable]
    H -- No --> J{Group of assertions?}
    J -- Yes --> K[assertAll]
    J -- No --> L[assertSame / assertNotSame]
```

**Reading the diagram:** Use this as a **decision aid** during the lab exam when you must pick the right assertion for a given scenario. KTU often asks: *"Which assertion would you use to verify that a method throws an exception?"* — answer: `assertThrows`.

---

## 4.4 Coverage vs. Mutation Testing — Why Both Are Needed

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    A[100% Line Coverage] --> B{All assertions strong?}
    B -- Yes --> C[High Mutation Score]
    B -- No --> D[Tests with weak assertions]
    D --> E[Many LIVE mutants survive]
    E --> F[Add targeted assertions]
    F --> C
    C --> G[Robust Test Suite]
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The diagram shows a **causal chain**: 100% line coverage is *necessary but not sufficient*. Without strong assertions, mutants survive. Only after strengthening assertions do we obtain a high mutation score and a truly robust test suite.

