### Question 2 `[KTU University Exam — Dec 2023, Module 1, 3 marks]`

**Q: Explain the role of the `@BeforeEach` annotation in JUnit 5. Why is a new test-class instance created for every `@Test` method?**

**Model Answer:**

- `@BeforeEach` is a JUnit 5 lifecycle annotation. The method annotated with `@BeforeEach` runs **before every `@Test` method** in the class. It is typically used to **set up a fresh test fixture** — for example, creating a new instance of the class under test, initialising test data, opening database connections, etc.
- JUnit 5 creates a **new instance of the test class for every `@Test` method** to guarantee **test isolation**. If a test method modifies a field (e.g., changes `account.balance`), that change must not leak into the next test. By re-instantiating, each test starts from a known clean state.
- This avoids *order-dependent failures* and is one of the major design improvements over JUnit 4 (which used a single instance per class).

