## 5.3 KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Pitfall Callout

> [!WARNING]
> **Where students lose marks on this topic (read carefully before exam):**
>
> 1. **Forgetting to subtract equivalent mutants** in the denominator of the Mutation Score formula. Always write $M_t - M_{eq}$, not just $M_t$.
> 2. **Confusing Mutation Score with Coverage.** Coverage is about *lines executed*; mutation score is about *faults detected*. Examiners specifically test this distinction.
> 3. **Mixing up JUnit 4 and JUnit 5 annotations.** Use `@BeforeEach` and `@AfterEach` (JUnit 5), **not** `@Before` and `@After` (JUnit 4 — outdated).
> 4. **Not mentioning test isolation** when asked why a new instance is created per test. This is a guaranteed 1-mark item.
> 5. **Forgetting to name mutation operators with their acronyms** (AOR, ROR, LOR, COD). Examiners often award 0.5 marks for *just the acronym* and another 0.5 for the *correct example*.
> 6. **Writing code without explanation.** A bare JUnit test class without prose earns only ~50% of marks. Always add a short paragraph explaining the *intent* of each test.
> 7. **Ignoring the cost trade-off.** Mutation testing is computationally expensive (mutants × test runs). Mention this in long-answer questions to show maturity.
> 8. **Confusing PIT with JUnit.** PIT is a *mutation testing* tool; JUnit is a *unit testing* framework. They are not the same thing.

