## 5.4 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Rapid Revision Checklist — print this page the night before the exam.**
>
> - **Unit Testing** = testing the smallest testable part in isolation.
> - **JUnit 5** = Jupiter API; uses `@Test`, `@BeforeEach`, `@AfterEach`, `@BeforeAll`, `@AfterAll`, `@DisplayName`, `@Disabled`, `@ParameterizedTest`, `@Nested`.
> - **New instance per `@Test`** → test isolation guarantee.
> - **Key assertions:** `assertEquals`, `assertTrue/False`, `assertNull/NotNull`, `assertThrows`, `assertAll`, `assertSame`.
> - **Mutation Testing** = inject faults → run test suite → classify mutants as **killed / live / equivalent**.
> - **Mutation Score formula:** $MS = \dfrac{M_k}{M_t - M_{eq}} \times 100$.
> - **Industry threshold:** $MS \ge 80\%$ for a "good" test suite.
> - **Five core mutation operators:** AOR, ROR, LOR, COD, UOI.
> - **Equivalent mutants** must be subtracted in the denominator.
> - **PIT (Pitest)** is the standard Java mutation testing tool — integrates with Maven/Gradle/Jenkins.
> - **JUnit ≠ PIT.** JUnit runs tests on original code; PIT runs tests on mutated code.
> - **Cost of mutation testing** = $n$ × (cost of single test run) where $n$ = number of mutants.
> - **Case study recipe:** (1) Define a small class with branches & exceptions, (2) Write JUnit tests with strong assertions, (3) Run PIT, (4) Identify surviving mutants, (5) Add tests, (6) Re-run until $MS \ge 80\%$.
> - **Always pair structural coverage with mutation score** — coverage tells you *what was executed*; mutation score tells you *what faults were caught*.

